eb). Mathlib does not yet provide these, so the Lean file can only capture the problem’s data and a trivial example with placeholder conclusions. Once the necessary lemmas enter Mathlib, the existing scaffold—complete with explicit hypotheses, a trivial instance, and consistent simp lemmas—will allow the formal proof to mirror the informal argument precisely.", :reason-message "Exceeded retry budget after 4 failures", :status :abandoned, :problem-id "apm-a02J02", :at "2026-03-30T22:42:39.093006908Z", :last-phase :execute, :phase-notes {:observe "**WHAT IS REALLY BEING ASKED**  \nWe work on the probability space \\([0,1]\\) with Lebesgue measure and fix \\(1<p<\\infty\\). A sequence \\(\\{f_n\\}\\subset L^p([0,1])\\) converges almost everywhere to some \\(f\\in L^p([0,1])\\), and additionally the norms converge: \\(\\|f_n\\|_{L^p}\\to\\|f\\|_{L^p}\\). The question asks us to prove that the convergence is actually strong in \\(L^p\\); i.e. \\(\\|f_n-f\\|_{L^p}\\to0\\). In other words, almost-everywhere convergence together with convergence of the \\(L^p\\) norms forces convergence in the \\(L^p\\)-metric.\n\n**WHY IT IS HARD**  \nPointwise convergence plus norm convergence does not automatically imply strong convergence without some structure—counterexamples exist if \\(p=1\\) or \\(p=\\infty\\). The key issue is controlling the “loss of mass” in the limit: we must show that the \\(L^p\\) norm of the difference cannot stay away from zero when the individual norms already match. Students often try to pass to the limit under the integral directly, but without knowing \\(f_n-f\\to0\\) in some integrable sense, dominated convergence cannot be applied yet. The real tool is uniform convexity of \\(L^p\\) (or Clarkson’s inequalities/Mazur’s lemma), which converts norm convergence plus weak convergence into strong convergence. Recognizing that \\(L^p\\) spaces for \\(1<p<\\infty\\) are uniformly convex, or equivalently that the norm satisfies the parallelogram-type inequalities needed to apply the Brezis–Lieb lemma, is the prerequisite being tested.", :propose "**THE KEY INSIGHT**  \nUse the uniform convexity of \\(L^p\\) (for \\(1<p<\\infty\\)) or, equivalently, the Brezis–Lieb lemma. Since \\(f_n\\to f\\) a.e., Brezis–Lieb states that \\(\\|f_n\\|_p^p = \\|f\\|_p^p + \\|f_n-f\\|_p^p + o(1)\\). But the norms \\(\\|f_n\\|_p\\) converge to \\(\\|f\\|_p\\), so the leading terms cancel and force \\(\\|f_n-f\\|_p\\to0\\). Another viewpoint: a.e. convergence implies \\(f_n\\rightharpoonup f\\) weakly in \\(L^p\\). In a uniformly convex Banach space, weak convergence plus convergence of norms yields strong convergence. Either way, the crucial idea is to exploit the strict/uniform convexity of the \\(L^p\\) norm to rule out any “missing mass” in the limit.\n\n**THE NAIVE APPROACH THAT FAILS**  \nA first attempt is to use dominated convergence on \\(|f_n-f|^p\\) or to conclude directly that \\(|f_n|^p\\to|f|^p\\) in \\(L^1\\) because the norms converge. But without control of \\(|f_n|^p\\) by an integrable dominating function, dominated convergence cannot be applied, and the equality of norms alone does not imply convergence of the integrals of \\(|f_n-f|^p\\). Another common misstep is to deduce \\(\\|f_n-f\\|_p = |\\|f_n\\|_p - \\|f\\|_p|\\), which is false unless the functions are colinear. The obstruction is that a.e. convergence and norm convergence do not provide any quantitative bound on \\(f_n-f\\); only the deeper structural property (uniform convexity / Brezis–Lieb) ties those two pieces of information together.", :execute "Stage 1 — THE CLEAN PROOF\n--------------------------------\n\nBecause \\(1<p<\\infty\\), \\(L^p([0,1])\\) is uniformly convex (hence has the Kadec–Klee property). Almost-everywhere convergence \\(f_n\\to f\\) implies \\(f_n\\rightharpoonup f\\) weakly in \\(L^p\\). In a uniformly convex space, weak convergence together with convergence of norms forces strong convergence: if \\(f_n\\rightharpoonup f\\) and \\(\\|f_